value.value: The epithelium of upper vagina (syn: epithelial layer of upper part of vagina) (TS:24-TS:27). The epithelial layer of the upper vagina is selectively marked by Wnt7a at E17 (absent from sinovaginal bulb epithelium) (Abler et al, 2011).

The muscle of upper vagina (syn: muscular layer of upper part of vagina) (TS:24-TS:27) is the smooth muscle layer of the upper vagina. Marked by Crabp1 at E17 (Abler et al, 2011) and alpha smooth muscle actin and gamma smooth muscle actin.

The epithelium of sinovaginal bulb: (syn: epithelium of lower vagina, vaginal bulb epithelium, vaginal plate) (TS:24-TS:27). Krt14 at E17 is specific to the epithelial layer of sinovaginal bulb (Krt14 also present in urothelium of bladder, but absent from epithelial layer of upper vagina) (Abler et al, 2011).
The muscle of sinovaginal bulb (syn: muscular layer of lower vagina) (TS:24-TS:27) is marked by Crabp1 E17 (Abler et al, 2011) and alpha smooth muscle actin and gamma smooth muscle actin.
The genital tubercle mesenchyme of male (gtm) (TS:20-20) is the mesenchyme of the genital tubercle surrounding the epithelium of phallic urethra of male.

value.value: The preputial swelling of male (pps) (syn: preputial fold of male, early prepuce of male) (TS:21-TS:23). Two lateral swellings develop on the sides of the genital tubercle at TS:21 and grow medially and ventrally. These swellings enclose the preputial glands. Comprised of skin of male preputial swelling, preputial gland of male, and mesenchyme of male preputial swelling.  At TS:24, when the two preputial swellings join/fuse together at the ventral midline of the genital tubercle of male, they become the prepuce of male.

The glans of male genital tubercle (TS:23-TS:24) is the distal part of the genital tubercle of male, comprised of skin and mesenchyme of glans of male genital tubercle. Derived from distal genital tubercle of male. The distal end of the phallic urethra of male is located within the glans, including the urethral plate epithelium of male and part of the urethral tube epithelium of male. Becomes the glans penis at TS:25, when genital tubercle of male becomes penis.

value.value: The genital tubercle mesenchyme of female (gtm) (TS:20-20) is the mesenchyme of the genital tubercle surrounding the epithelium of phallic urethra of female.

The male urethral gland (ur gland) (TS:27-TS:28). Numerous epithelial urethral glands develop from the epithelium of the urethra. Develop from male urethral gland bud (TS:24-26). Part of the urethra of male, subdivided into urethral gland of male pelvic urethra (part of the pelvic urethra) and urethral gland of penile urethra (part of the penile urethra).

The female urethral gland (ur gland) (syn: Skene's gland) (TS:27-TS:28). Epithelial urethral glands develop from the epithelium of the urethra. Develop from female urethral gland bud (TS:24-TS:26). Part of the urethra of female, subdivided into urethral gland of pelvic urethra of female (part of the pelvic urethra) and urethral gland of clitoral urethra (part of the clitoral urethra).

value.value: The anterior prostate gland (aprgl) (syn: coagulating gland) (TS:28). Prostate glands are subdivided into four bilaterally symmetrical regions (known as lobes in the human); anterior, dorsal, lateral and ventral prostate gland. The regions have different morphology and gene expression profiles which are specified during development via both common and region-specific genetic pathways. The 3D anatomy of the prostate gland is extremely complex.
